Kelly Mazzante scored 22 points and became Penn State's career scoring
leader as the No. 9 Lady Lions beat No. 12 LSU 83-46 Friday night.
article.headline: Lady Lions hang lop-sided win on LSU
article.linkText: Penn State tops LSU; Mazzante tops school scoring chart
article.story:
STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Kelly Mazzante would have preferred to
break the record with one shot instead of three.

Mazzante scored 22 points and became Penn State's career scoring
leader as the No. 9 Lady Lions beat No. 12 LSU 83-46 Friday night.

Mazzante made two free throws to tie the mark, then broke it
after she was fouled again 13 seconds later.

"I would rather have had it come on a 3 than a free throw,"
Mazzante said. "It put a little bit more pressure on me, and
everyone started yelling."

Mazzante, who came into the game 15 points behind Susan
Robinson, has 2,260 points career points. Robinson scored 2,253
points from 1989-92.

"We all knew that it was the record and she was going to break
it today, but I don't think we were trying to force the ball to
her," Jess Strom said. "She was going to get it anyway."

Besides, by the time Mazzante broke the record, Penn State
didn't need the points.

Mazzante's free throws were part of a 14-0 run -- she scored nine
points in the outburst -- as the Lady Lions (1-0) took a 70-36 lead
with 7:36 left.

LSU (1-2), which opened the season ranked ninth, lost its second
straight following a season-opening 76-67 setback at Oregon. The
Lady Tigers shot 18-for-52 from the field.

"I have never been so thankful that this is only the third game
of the season," LSU coach Sue Gunter said. "I really would be
frightened. But we didn't have any answers tonight for anything
that Penn State wanted to do. Offensively, defensively, on the
boards, transition -- they pretty much had their way."

Mazzante didn't score until the 13-minute mark of the first
half, but by that point Penn State had opened an 18-5 lead. Tanisha
Wright's pull-up jumper with 11 seconds left made it 48-26 at
halftime.

"I thought one of the things that was terrifically important
for us tonight was to get off to a good start, and I thought the
first five minutes were absolutely critical to us," Gunter said.

Wright had 15 points, eight rebounds and eight assists for Penn
State. Jess Brungo scored 12, and Strom 10.

"It was nice to see a lot of people contribute, but it was the
calmness of Kelly that made it happen," Penn State coach Rene
Portland said.

A preseason All-American, Mazzante was the first freshman to
lead the Big Ten in scoring, and she has led the conference in
scoring every season since. She led the nation in scoring in her
sophomore season, averaging 24.9 points.

In breaking the record, Mazzante did a little bit of everything,
hitting two 3-pointers, driving the lane, even posting up on the
block. She also finished with five rebounds, three assists and two
steals.

"Kelly's just a great scorer. She's not just a shooter, she's a
scorer," Gunter said. "I think sometimes we forget that she also
does a good job on the boards and plays good defense, as well."

Temeka Johnson led LSU with 18 points, and Seimone Augustus add
12.
